## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

---

### 5.1 PART A Questions (3 Marks Each)

**Q1. `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`**  
**What is form validation? Why is JavaScript commonly used for client-side form validation?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

Form validation is the process of ensuring that user-entered data in an HTML form meets the required rules of format, completeness, and correctness before being submitted.

JavaScript is widely used for client-side form validation because:
1. It executes **in the user's browser** without requiring a page reload, providing instant feedback.
2. It allows access to form elements via the **Document Object Model (DOM)**, making it easy to read values and display errors.
3. It supports **Regular Expressions** for powerful pattern matching (emails, phone numbers, etc.).
4. It improves **user experience** and reduces unnecessary server requests with invalid data. **(3 marks)**

---

**Q2. `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`**  
**Differentiate between client-side validation and server-side validation. Which is more secure and why?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

| Aspect | Client-Side Validation | Server-Side Validation |
|---|---|---|
| Where it runs | In the user's browser (via JavaScript) | On the web server (e.g., PHP, Node.js, Python) |
| Speed | Very fast, instant feedback | Slower (network round-trip required) |
| Security | Can be bypassed by disabling JavaScript | Cannot be bypassed; trusted source |
| Purpose | First line of defense — UX enhancement | Authoritative — data integrity and security |

**Server-side validation is more secure** because it cannot be disabled or bypassed by the user. JavaScript on the client can be turned off, manipulated via DevTools, or skipped entirely — so sensitive checks (authentication, authorization, database writes) must always be validated on the server. **(3 marks)**

