## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

An **Image Slider** (also called a *Carousel* or *Slideshow Component*) is a dynamic web user interface (UI) component that sequentially displays a series of images within a fixed visual container, providing interactive user navigation through *Previous* and *Next* control mechanisms. In the context of the KTU **GXESL208 - IT Workshop** syllabus under the **2024 Scheme**, this experiment is designed to develop competency in the foundational triad of front-end web engineering: **HTML (HyperText Markup Language)** for semantic structural scaffolding, **CSS (Cascading Style Sheets)** for presentational rendering, and **JavaScript (ECMAScript)** for client-side behavioral logic and DOM (Document Object Model) manipulation.

The core engineering challenge is implementing a **stateful cycling mechanism** where a single image index variable tracks the currently displayed image, and two event-driven functions (`prev()` and `next()`) modify that index state with **circular wrap-around logic** (i.e., sliding past the last image returns to the first, and vice versa).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Scheme Learning Outcome Mapping:**
> This experiment primarily satisfies **CO2**: *Create interactive web pages using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript* and **CO3**: *Apply client-side scripting techniques for DOM manipulation*. It tests **Bloom's Level 3 (Apply)** and **Level 4 (Analyze)** cognitive skills as per Revised Bloom's Taxonomy under the NEP 2020 framework.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition (Plain English)

Imagine you are holding a **physical photograph album** with **5 pictures** stacked inside. The album has a single viewing window that shows **only one picture at a time**.

- The **"Next" button** is like flipping the album page to the right, revealing the next picture. When you reach the **last (5th) picture**, pressing "Next" magically cycles the album back to the **1st picture** (this is called *circular navigation*).
- The **"Previous" button** is like flipping the album page to the left, showing the previous picture. When you are on the **1st picture** and press "Previous", it cycles back to the **5th (last) picture**.

In technical terms:
- The **photo album** = the HTML `<div>` container
- The **photographs** = the array of image sources `["img1.jpg", "img2.jpg", ...]`
- The **currently visible page number** = a JavaScript variable `let currentIndex = 0;`
- **Flipping the page** = calling the `next()` or `prev()` function which mutates `currentIndex`

### 1.3 Standard Engineering Metrics (Bolded for Emphasis)

- **Total Image Count (N)**: The total number of images in the slider array.
- **Current Index (i)**: Zero-based integer index ranging from **0 to N−1**.
- **Wrap-Around Modulus Operation**: `newIndex = (oldIndex + 1) % N` for next, and `newIndex = (oldIndex - 1 + N) % N` for previous.
- **Image Transition**: Typically implemented as a CSS opacity crossfade or simple `src` attribute swap with a duration of **300ms–500ms** for professional UX.

> [!NOTE]
> **Why this experiment matters in industry:** Image sliders are the cornerstone UI pattern of e-commerce hero banners (Amazon, Flipkart), news websites (BBC, CNN), and portfolio websites. Mastering this teaches you **state management**, **event-driven programming**, and **DOM traversal** — three skills used in every modern JavaScript framework (React, Vue, Angular).

