**Q2. [KTU University Exam - June 2024, Model Paper 1]**

**Explain the purpose of the modulo operator (%) in the image slider logic. Why is the expression `(currentIndex - 1 + N) % N` used instead of simply `(currentIndex - 1) % N`?**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**

The **modulo operator (%)** returns the remainder of a division operation. In the image slider, it is used to implement **circular navigation** — ensuring that pressing "Next" on the last image returns to the first, and pressing "Previous" on the first image returns to the last.

The expression `(currentIndex - 1) % N` is **incorrect** because JavaScript's modulo operator returns a **negative result for negative operands**. For example, when `currentIndex = 0`, the naive formula gives `(-1) % N = -1`, which would attempt to access `images[-1]`, resulting in `undefined`.

By adding `N` first: `(currentIndex - 1 + N) % N`, the dividend becomes positive (e.g., for `currentIndex = 0` and `N = 4`: `(-1 + 4) = 3`, and `3 % 4 = 3`), correctly returning the last image's index.

*(Award 1 mark for explaining modulo's role, 2 marks for the negative-modulo pitfall explanation — 3 marks total.)*

